tionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."],"variants":[{"name":"Lammert","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]},{"name":"Lamprecht","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lambert de Warluzel was born in 1112, in Warluzel, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Auguste de Warluzel, was 34 and his mother, Gertrude de Marieux, was 28. He married Jehanne de Humbercourt in 1138, in Humbercourt, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1169, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1112–1169":"1112–1169","1122–